  "text": "Normal-hearing listeners can detect amplitude changes over a 100-dB acoustic dynamic range with a high resolution. The total number of discriminable intensity steps for normal acoustic hearing, as calculated from Weber fractions reported by [CITATION_1] , was found to be over 80 [CITATION_2] . The large dynamic range coupled with fine intensity resolution and fine spectral resolution, allows normal-hearing listeners to maintain h igh speech intelligibility in background noise and in extreme signal conditions lacking traditional spectral cues.",
